column168: A sales and service representative accepted an 85gal. over-pack poly drum that contained a 55gal. steel drum containing Sulfuric Acid. The poly over-pack drum was loaded onto a box truck and transported without incident. The poly over-pack drum was offloaded at a warehouse by use of a drum dolly and placed on the concrete floor. A week after being offloaded, the poly over-pack drum was found to have leaked approx. 1Gal. of material onto the concrete floor. Once mitigation was performed the breach in the poly over-pack was determined to be a small pin-hole in the bottom of the poly over-pack drum most likely caused by a puncture.
column169: The branch employees that handle material in the warehouse will be re-trained regarding proper handling of drums, from loading, offloading to placement for in-transit storage within the warehouse. The crew will also be re-trained on container inspection.

Highway Transport was traveling north on I-85 when he came upon traffic stopped in both lanes on the interstate. As HT driver attempted to brake V-1 came across from far left lane to the shoulder attempting to stop but was unable to stop before entering onto the right shoulder. V-2 (HT) trying to avoid V-1 went to the right shoulder and then into the median resulting in CMV laying over on its side.  Once the trailer came to rest on it's right side, product pushing against the 4" pressure relief valve (PRV) mounted inside the crash box began to leak product. Once the product drained below the PRV it sealed and the leak stopped. We are unsure of the duration of the leak but it did stop. A dike was built to contain the product at the trailer placement.
column169: Driver has been interviewed as part of our internal investigation. Courses has been put in place for Complacency Training, Distracted Driving, and Safe Methods of Operating a Tank Truck. These course were established to provide our drivers with retaining and periodic training as needed.   I believe there are an enormous amount of training and regulations in place both federally and locally to transport hazardous materials in a safe manner. The only possible recommendation would be maybe enforcing stricter training on all hazmat drivers on all levels of the transportation industry. An example would be to shorten the Hazardous Materials test to maybe every six months instead of the current period.

column168: Five drums of aviation fuel were accepted from Servion Air FBO at TSTC airport in Waco, TX. These drums were transported to the Waco Safety-Kleen Systems, INC. 10 day facility without incident. Upon a container inspection by a CHESi National Trans Van driver, the drums were found to have an unacceptable amount of corrosion around the bottom chime and various other places on the body of the drums. The driver conducting the container inspection rubbed a corroded area of the drum at the chime and caused some material to flake off and  created a small pin hole leak on two different drums. Between the two drums approximately 2 oz. of aviation fuel was released on the concrete floor of the warehouse.
column169: This release was a result of insufficient container inspection being conducted by the service representatives that accepted the drums. After an investigative call with the management team and the involved employees, it was determined that the entire branch staff would under go a series of remedial trainings to include container inspection. Since the occurrence of this release, the management team has delivered the remedial training and submitted a signed training roster with all participants listed. The management team has also conducted an audit of other drums stored in their warehouse to identify any drums that may be stored that require over-packing to avoid a potential release.

column168: 2021-05-03 CN Hawthorne Yard, IL - FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector noted liquid coming from the top of tank car DBCX 201553 (L / Formic Acid/ UN1779/ Class 8 (3)/ PG II) while conducting his duties at the CN Hawthorne Yard in Cicero, IL.  All appropriate departments notified with tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting security seals intact and noting liquid coming from the liquid valve securement flange. The liquid valve was found to be in the fully closed position but not creating a secured seal allowing liquid to bypass the valve seat to the upper flange gasket (also found damaged) and out of a flange securement bolt hole. The car exterior was cleaned, liquid valve replaced by a certified repair facility and released to transportation for further movement.

column168: On May 14, 2021, at 3:10 am CDT, a representative with R+L Carriers (RLC) at the above-referenced location observed one (1) 375-gallon tote containing ethyl acetate on trailer SF0880 that experienced a valve failure. As a result, approximately three (3) gallons of product released to the trailer floor and further migrated to the concrete parking lot. column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE EMULSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE SUSPENSION OR AMMONIUM NITRATE GEL, INTERMEDIATE FOR BLASTING EXPLOSIVES
column168: Around 12:30 PM on May 3, 2021, a company driver was pumping ammonium nitrate emulsion (UN3375) off of a tanker (DOT 407) into a bin at the Austin location in Knightdale, NC. The driver was a few minutes into the process, and reported that the pump appeared to be functioning correctly, and operating at a standard pressure around 70-75 PSI.  The driver walked away from the unloading location to deliver paperwork up to the office.  He was away from the scene for a few minutes according to his statement. This is against our company policy of driver remaining in attendance when offloading bulk product.  When he returned, it was discovered that  the bulk product was pouring out onto the gravel lot, and pooling beneath the tanker.  The driver immediately cut off the PTO, closed the valve to the bin, and contacted his dispatcher.  In total it is estimated that roughly 6,000 lbs. of product was released.  All of it was contained to the gravel lot, remaining pooled in a large puddle about 20 feet in diameter.  A local environmental response was called, and responded within a couple hours.  The product was vacuumed up to the extent practicable, and the remaining impacted soil and gravel was shoveled up  and containerized.  Some of the product will be eligible for commercial use.  The unusable product and residual waste water that was generated from cleaning the vacuum is being profiled and will be disposed of in accordance with EPA regulations.  An inspection of the scene revealed a blown 100 PSI burst disk.  A pressure spike had caused the disk to burst, and as a result, product was shot out of the outlet valve and onto the ground.  Upon returning to a company shop, the tanker was inspected. A "headlamp" flashlight was found at the bottom of the tanker, obstructing the internal valve.  It is thought that the pressure spike was likely caused by the obstruction.
column169: 1. Training issues:  Drivers will be retrained to follow the policy of staying in attendance when bulk product is being transferred off of a tanker into a bin.  Drivers and load crews will be retrained securing any loose items when working over a hatch, and in reporting to management any time a foreign object is accidentally dropped into a tank. 2. Possible quality issues are being addressed with our supplier of burst disks 3. Company engineers are designing a system that would allow a length of hose to be attached to discharge outlet and go back up into tank.  This would be in place during transfer of product, and would prevent bulk material from being discharged onto the ground when burst disk fails.

Antoine Ivy with Central Transport called to report a possible hazmat release. It was reported a driver pulled over in a toll plaza and was leaking product from a tote onto I-90 and into a storm drain. He didn't have any additional information. ERTS contacted the driver for more information. He said the product is a UN1760 Sanitizer and he lost all 250 gallons on the outbound side of the toll plaza. Hazchem is on-site reviewing conditions. Hazchem advised that the entire tote released, escaped the trailer, and ran along the curb for about 100' before entering the storm drain. Hazchem has a vacuum truck in route to work on recovery from the drain. Hazchem will use a pallet jack and forklift to remove the freight from the trailer. HazChem personnel advised that they applied oil dri to the impacted area of roadway and collected it. Hazchem personnel applied oil dri to the rear of the trailer. Hazchem personnel utilized their vacuum truck to flush out collect the liquid in the storm drain. Approximately 100 gallons of product impacted liquids were collected and will be taken off site for disposal. Central Transport personnel will conduct the clean up of the freight trailer.

column168: Tank Car TCLX, outbound load of diesel fuel, was observed with product dripping from the bottom outlet cap on Friday, May 7 at approximately 1337 hours. At inspection there was one drip approximately every 10 seconds.  PTRA contacted M&M Protection to respond and address the leaking tank car along with another car in the cut with a loose bottom outlet cap.  This is the report from M&M... Friday 05/07/2021 M&M Emergency and Environmental Services (M&M) responded to the PTRA North Yard at the request of Mr. Kirk Higbie, Port Terminal Railroad Association. Mr. Higbie indicated that railcar TCLX 318015 was leaking from the bottom outlet valve while railcar GBRX 705436 was reported to have a non-conforming bottom outlet valve housing. Both railcars were in a string of cars located on track #59. Mr. Higbie requested the railcars be repaired and readied for shipment. John McHazlett, M&M’s Director of Operations arrived on site and contacted the on-duty Trainmaster Mr. David Richardson. Mr. Richardson agreed to let M&M personnel lock out the switches on track #59 associated with the leaking railcars. After the tracks were locked out M&M personnel began the assessment on the GBRX 705436. After concluding the repairs to GBRX705436, M&M personnel mistakenly moved to railcar TCLX318031 and began an assessment of the bottom outlet adapter. TCLX318031 was not the correct car which M&M had been called to repair. The actual car to be repaired was TCLX318015 which was on the same track #59 but located about some car lengths south of TCLX318031. While addressing the bottom outlet adapter M&M personnel observed a slightly wet area around the outlet valve threads. The adapter was only hand tight and not fastened securely to the car. M&M personnel removed the bottom outlet housing, inspected the elastomeric gasket for a correct fitting. The gasket appeared to be in good order with no cracks, or seat etching. The bottom outlet adapter was reinstalled onto TCLX318031 and securely fastened to the bottom outlet valve. After completing repairs to GBRX705436, and the misidentified second leaking car TCLX318031 M&M personnel contacted the Train Master and relayed that all repairs had been made and locks removed. S
column169: It was not until assembling this final report on 05/17/2021 that M&M realized the discrepancy between repairing TCLX318031 and TCLX318015. Upon the discovery Mr. Kirk Higbie with PTRA and Mr. Roy Gonzales with the FRA were both notified by M&M senior management that railcar TCLX318031 had been worked on versus the original call out for TCLX318015. M&M Emergency Response & Environmental Services regrets the oversight and accepts full responsibility for the crew misidentification of the car to be repaired. At no time did PTRA or M&M choose or decide not to make the needed repairs to TCLX318015. At the time M&M personnel had onsite the needed equipment and manpower to make all repairs and or product transfers to assure for a safe and compliant railcar. However, in this incidence M&M personnel incorrectly identified the railcar to be worked on and when the error was realized the correct car to be repaired had been moved. M&M’s internal investigation has caused all employees to focus on confirming the work to be completed, with a required redundant written and pictorial verification of all work performed before and after.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: At 1419 Hours, the WLE Rook Yard train crew notice liquid product down the sides of tank car NATX 310419 while observing an inbound train.  They notified the Rook Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials and Environmental Officer for the WLE.  Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA was then called to go out and assess the car.  They found fresh product on the sides of the car that looked like it was coming from the manway from around the area of the manway lid lid handle.  They removed seal SLY100192 from the manway lid and opened it up to check the gasket.  It was reported that the manway bolts were indeed tight.  The gasket did not look compromised to the point that it would leak but it was evident that product was coming out from the lid.  A new nozzle type gasket was installed replacing the ring style gasket in the lid. A new seal  #5973321 was installed on the manway.  They removed seal SLY100191 from the Protective housing cover so that they could open it and make sure that product wasn't coming from any of the valve.  They did not find any evidence of a leak.  The installed a new seal #5973312 on the protective housing lid. The product was then wiped off the sides of the car and the car was released into transportation.

column168: MC Tank contacted ERTS requesting ERTS coordinate with a network contractor to respond to a cargo tank incident. Jeff requested a contractor to respond to the site to change out a 4"-8 bulb flange gasket. M.C. Tank stated the driver noticed the bolts were loose and tightened them however, the gasket is still dripping Naphthalene at a slow rate of 1-2 drops per minute into a 5 gallon bucket. The environmental contractor (EES) arrived on site and located the tanker. There is a bucket under the tank catching the leak. 1 gallon is in the bucket. There is a spill of 1 gallon of Naphthalene on the roadside soil in a 2' x 2' area. EES found that the primary shutoff valve under the tank is not fully closing. EES has the leaking flange sealed at this time and the gasket tightened up. M.C. Tank supplied a replacement CTMV and EES personnel conducted a product transfer. The area of impacted soil was removed and backfilled with existing fill. The minimal waste was collected and taken off site for pending disposal

column168: On 5/1/2021 at 1100 ET, one (1) 275 - gallon tote was dropped with a forklift while unloading due to poor weather conditions. As a result, approximately 125 gallons of UN1993, Flammable liquid, NOS (Xylene Ethylbenzene), 3, PGIII (Xylene) PGIII "Keropur AP NA4M" released impacting the asphalt parking lot and nearby soil. E3 Environmental was dispatched to perform cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival, personnel transferred the product remaining in the tote into a new tote, approximately 150 gallons. The contractor applied granular absorbents to the impacted area of asphalt. The impacted area of soil was hand excavated. The spent absorbents and impacted soil were collected and consolidated into one supersack. The contractor was able to recover free standing liquids, Keropur AP NA4M impacted rainwater, into three (3) 95 - gallon overpack drums and six (6) 55 - gallon metal drums. The contractor then staged the waste onsite and departed the site.

column168: DRIVER FOUND THAT THE PACKAGE WAS SPILLING IN THE BOTTOM OF HIS TRUCK AND TRIED TO CONTAIN IT HIMSELF WITH PAPER TOWELS AND PLASTIC BAGS. CALLED CENTER MANAGEMENT TO REPORT THE LEAK AND FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. UPON ARRIVAL, THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER FOUND THAT THE SUBSTANCE HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE GROUND. CLEANING HAD BEEN STOPPED TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT ABOUT THE SPILL OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE CAR. OUTSIDE RESPONDER HAD BEEN CALLED FOR THE OUTSIDE OF THE VEHICLE. DESIGNATED RESPONDER CONTINUED CLEAN UP IN THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS GENERATING HEAT. DESIGNATED RESPONDER THEN STOPPED CLEAN UP TO UPDATE SAFETY MANAGEMENT OF THE CHANGING CONDITION. CLEAN UP WAS THEN STOPPED FOR THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER TO TAKE OVER TRUCK CLEAN UP.

column168: While attempting to transfer by hand a 30 gallon container weighing approximately 150 lbs and classified as Flammable Solid material (Cyclohexane and Isopropyl alcohol with absorbents), from one pallet to an adjacent pallet within our 10-Day Storage Facility in Port Allen, La, the drum cracked along the sidewall as it was placed onto the pallet. This ~18 inch crack allowed approximately 5-10 gallons of free liquid to spill from the container. The Veolia employee handling the drum set the container down and leaned it against a pallet to reduce the magnitude of the leak. Another employee poured oil dry absorbent material onto the spill, which was contained to a 10x10 ft area within the warehouse. The drum was lifted up and placed into a 951H2 overpack drum filled 1/3 of the way with oil dry in order to absorb up any remaining free liquid that may leak from the original container. After allowing oil dry time to soak up liquid spilled on the ground, the absorbent was scooped up and placed into the overpack drum, which was then sealed. A Veolia supervisor was onsite and witnessed the spill and immediately informed the Veolia EHS Manager and General Manager of the incident. A discussion occurred regarding the integrity of these shipping containers that are used by this generator and there is concern behind why there is free liquid in these drums when the profile is setup to contain 75-90 percent absorbent, thus being classified as a flammable solid material. These issues will be investigated more thoroughly in the following days.
column169: In order to mitigate incidents such as this from occurring again and possibly leading to a more serious incident, the customer will be notified that these materials should be packaged into containers that are rated for liquids and the containers should be stored in a manner that does not negatively affect the integrity of the container. Routine handling, like moving a container from one pallet to another should not lead to a severe container failure such as the one that occurred in this incident. Also these waste streams should be reviewed with the customer to ensure that they are classified appropriately, thus mitigating issues such as free liquids being present in a flammable solid waste stream.

column168: May 25, 2021, Caitlin Witherspoon with Dana Companies (Suttles Truck Leasing)  contacted ERTS regarding a UN1993, Flammable Liquid, N.O.S., 3 PG III "Unisol Liquid Red BK" release that occurred at 1200 ET at Colonial Premier Terminal, 4227 Cromwell Rd. Chattanooga, TN. It was advised that 1 gallon of product released to the asphalt due to a pressurized hose cap during unloading. ERTS dispatched Hepaco (environmental contractor) to clean the impacted areas. No drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. Hepaco reports the spill covered 2 lanes at the fuel island (areas 30ft x 60ft ) as well as all the pipes and pumps. Hepaco's plan of action is to use oil dry to get the heaviest impacted parts then use muriatic acid mixture for the concrete. They will need to use diesel fuel and degreaser to clean off the pipes and pumps at the fuel island. Hepaco completed the initial clean up operations. Site personnel coordinated the additional power washing and clean up operations with alternate environmental personnel. Hepaco personnel collected the waste they generated and took it off site for pending disposal.

column168: On May 24, 2021, at approximately 7:20 a.m. CDT, personnel at the above-referenced terminal owned by R+L Carriers (RLC) were loading cargo by forklift when a pallet containing 1-quart containers of paint (UN3469) and 5-gallon pales of paint (UN1263) shifted inside the trailer, damaging the containers. As a result, approximately three (3) gallons of paint (UN3469) and five (5) gallons of paint (UN1263) was released to the trailer interior and adjacent cargo. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from UST Environmental Contractor (UST) to perform the necessary corrective action. UST personnel noted approximately  three (3) gallons of paint (UN3469) and five (5) gallons of paint (UN1263) was released to the trailer interior and adjacent cargo. The crew removed the pallets from the trailer and down stacked the pallets to collect the damaged containers. UST personnel collected 18 damaged / 9 impacted 1-quart containers of paint (UN3469) and containerized as waste. The crew then collected six (6) damaged 5-gallon pales of paint (UN1263) and containerized as waste. UST personnel deployed granular absorbents to the trailer interior and worked in with hand tools. The crew then applied a paint thinner to the trailer floor and wiped down with absorbent wipes. UST personnel collected the paint impacted material (cardboard boxes, containers) then containerized as waste. The crew palletized the non-damaged 1-quart containers of paint (UN3469) and 5-gallon pales of paint (UN1263) for transport. All paint-impacted material and damaged containers were collected in one (1) 95-gallon over pack, two (2) 15-gallon over packs, and one (1) 35-gallon over pack. The waste was staged at RLC's terminal until disposal could be coordinated. UST personnel secured the site and scheduled to return to collect the waste pending disposal approval.

On 05/25/2021 at 1600 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Sumter Yard (Sumter, SC) discovered  GATX53691, a residue last contained tank car of flammable liquids N.O.S leaking from top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Giant Cement Co was notified, Hazmat Manager Joe Taylor  could hear pressure venting from the tank car around the manway. The manway was opened up  and it was discovered that there was not a manway gasket. The issue was identified and corrective  actions were communicated to the shipper, Giant Cement  (Damon Barton 843-701-0163). Mr. J. Taylor  relieved the pressure on the car and installed a new manway gasket and re-secured the manway.  The tank car was released back into transportation without delay.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING AN ALCOHOL-LIKE ODOR BY AN UNLOADER IN SECTION-B. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A COUPLE OF MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A MINISCULE PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF A PLASTIC 1-GAL JUG, APPARENTLY FROM AN EXTERNAL PROTRUDING SHARP OBJECT. THIS CAUSED APPROX. 4 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BOTTOM/SIDE OF CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 200 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

A PACKAGE WITH SHIPPING PAPERS AND A FLAMMABLE DIAMOND HAZARD LABEL WAS LEAKING IN THE DMP BEFORE IT WAS AUDITED. A DESIGNATED RESPONDER PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND LEFT IT IN THE DMP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: PACKAGE WAS A UN SPECIFIED DOUBLE WALL FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING ONE 5 GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER. LESS THAN 2 INCHES OF KRAFT PAPER WAS USED AS PACKING MATERIAL. THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT LOADED PROPERLY. IT WAS NOT RIGHT-SIDE-UP. IT WAS NOT LOADED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. IT APPEARS THE PRESSURE FROM PACKAGES THAT WERE LOADED ON TOP CAUSED THE CAP TO FAIL AND THE CONTAINER TO LEAK.

column168: On May 11 2021, upon loading IM container MRKU220716 onto a truck chassis from the NS IM yard, trucking personnel encountered strong smell and leaking from bottom of container.  NS hazmat was notified and sent a contractor to inspect the container with the only freight being documented as pallets of printing ink.  Upon inspection 1 of 2 drums of labeled cyclohexane had a gouge/puncture 1/3 way up side which resulted in product loss.  In addition to the 2 non declared drums, a bulk tote of marine pollutant was noted in the container not leaking but not declared.  Proper blocking/bracing was not applied to the lading.  The contractor used proper PPE and mitigated the leaking drum, cleaned up product and NS officials isolated the container in the yard while an investigation began and proper billing could be applied.

column168: On 5/22/2021 at 0700 ET, one (1) 15 - gallon poly drum of UN1824, Sodium hydroxide solution, 8, PGII was discovered to be leaking while being unloaded from a pinhole puncture caused by a nail. As a result, approximately 8 gallons of sodium hydroxide released impacting the trailer floor. Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance, Inc. was dispatched to the site to perform cleanup activities. The contractor overpacked the damaged drum into one (1) 55 - gallon poly drum. Personnel then applied granular absorbents to solidify the released product and utilized absorbent pads to decontaminate the impacted trailer floor. Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance, Inc. personnel then departed the site with the waste generated.

On 05/05/2021 a Veolia employee moved a shipment of drums from Americas Styrenics LLC with a forklift before leaving the Schenectady, NY transportation terminal at 3:00 PM. The following morning on 05/06/2021, employees arrived at the facility and discovered that a drum had leaked out of the primary container and into the trailer and asphalt containment area. The drum contained Styrene (Flammable Liquid). Employees discovered that a 55 gallon drum had been damaged with the forklift from the previous day.  Upon inspection it was determined that there was a large crack in the steel drum caused by a fork impacting the steel drum. The leaking drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum to contain the leak.     On 05/6/2021 the Veolia safety manager of Schenectady, NY and the facility manager investigated what occurred at the Schenectady, NY transportation terminal. It was discovered that employee simply misjudged the length of the fork and caused a dent and crack in the side of the Styrene drum. The Safety Manager and Facility Manager reviewed the paperwork and the amount of Styrene released. Fortunately, due to the viscosity of the Styrene, much of the Styrene remained in the primary container. It is estimated that about 12 gallons of Styrene was released. An evaluation was conducted to evaluate if a Reportable Quantity was released. The weight of the Styrene was 7.5 lbs. per gallon and 12 gallons was released. Total weight was 90 pounds therefore, the RQ was not met and immediate reporting to the NRC was not required.
column169: As part of the investigation on 05/06/21, the Veolia safety manager told the manager of the Veolia, Schenectady, NY facility that the employee who was operating the forklift could no longer operate the forklift until a review of the incident was conducted and that he would receive retraining.    The Veolia safety manager met with the facility manager and the employee on 05/20/2021 to review spill reporting procedures, investigate why the incident happened, and to retrain the employee on the forklift. The employee is fairly new to operating a forklift (less than 3 months) and he misjudged the forks of the lift. It was also later in the day and he may have ben rushing to get the large drum shipment transferred prior to leaving for the day.    In the future, the employee will be more careful when moving drums at the facility.

column168: PRELOAD EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A FEEDER. WHEN HE REACHED THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER HE SAW THAT PACKAGES HAD LIQUID ON THEM AND THERE WAS A STRONG SMELL. HE SAW THAT PACKAGES WERE DAMAGED AND THERE WAS AN OPEN HAZMAT PACKAGE THAT LOOKED LIKE IT HAD FALLEN FROM THE TOP OF A LOAD WALL AND BUSTED OPEN. THE CONTENTS OF THE HAZMAT HAD SPREAD TO OTHER PACKAGES AND ON TO FOREVER BAGS THAT CONTAINED SMALL PACKAGES. THE HAZMAT MATERIAL HAD CORRODED THE PACKAGES AROUND IT AND THE FOREVER BAGS CONTAINING THE SMALLS PACKAGES. HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO THEN NOTIFIED THE SORT MANAGER AND AN RMP. THE TRAILER CONTAINING THE PACKAGES WAS REMOVED FROM THE DOCK. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER AND THE RMP PUT ON PPE AND PROCEDED TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. DURING THE COURSE OF CHECKING THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGE VAPORS WERE SEEN RISING FROM SOME OF THE PACKAGES. AT THIS POINT THE CHAIN OF COMMAND WAS INACTED AND AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER SERVICE WAS CALLED.

column168: On 05/07/2021 at about 10:30 AM, a third party driver saw that a drum that was loaded onto his trailer prior to leaving the Schenectady, NY transportation had a two small pinholes in it. Veolia employees investigated the source of the leak and discovered that about 1 pint of Ethanol Solution leaked into the trailer below the drum and slightly wet the trailer floor. Upon inspection it was determined that there was a scuff in the steel drum where the pin holes were. The drum was scuffed about halfway down the drum. It is assumed that the holes and the scuff were caused by a fork truck loading other drums adjacent to the drum. The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum to contain the leak and the liquid on the trailer floor was cleaned up.
column169: The Veolia safety manager met with the facility manager on 05/20/2021 to review the spill and investigate why the incident happened. It is assumed that an employee loaded other drums too close to the drum that was scuffed and had two pin holes put in it.     In the future, employees operating forklifts will be retrained to be more careful when moving drums at the facility.

column168: Tank Car UTLX 212311 was discovered  leaking from the manway in the BNSF Argentine Yard in Kansas City, KS on May 28, 2021. Upon inspection, the manway bolts were found to be loose which allowed the manway to leak during movement. The secondary plugs on the liquid and vapor valves in the protective housing were also found to be less than tool tight. The secondary plugs did not leak.
column169: Review the securement and inspection procedures for the loading facility and re-train the loading/inspection personnel.(NAR:200)

column168: LOADING DAMAGE

On 05/12/2021 at about 12:40 PM, a Veolia employee entered the back of a box van after returning to the Veolia, Charlestown office. The employee noticed a blue liquid had leaked out of a three gallon plastic container and stained the label as well as slightly wet the floor of the truck below the container. The Veolia employee investigated the source of the leak and discovered that about 100 milliliters of a waste flammable liquid leaked into the box van. No liquid made it outside of the box van. Upon inspection it was determined that the cap of the container was not seated correctly on the 3 gallon drum and allowed the 100 milliliters of liquid to spill out. The cap was removed and replaced and secured with a hand tool to assure that it was closed according to the manufacturer's instructions. A new label was also placed on the container. The liquid on the trailer floor was cleaned up.
column169: The Veolia safety manager was notified of the incident by the facility manager on 05/12/2021. The two managers reviewed the incident details and decided the follow up action would be to discuss the incident with employees and also to review the incident with all employees during a weekly training to bring awareness to ensuring that containers are closed in accordance with the manufacturer closure instructions. The facility manager reviewed properly closing containers with employees at the facility and making sure that closures are seated correctly.

column168: During a daily site walk a Veolia manager noticed a small puddle under a trailer sitting in the dock area of the Veolia Stanley Ave site. The puddle was roughly 1 quart of paint related material. He immediately notified the on site material handler and they began cleaning up the spill under the trailer. After containing the spill trained Veolia employees began offloading the trailer to look for a potential cause. The employees identified a leaking CYD11G that was packed during a recent household hazardous waste event in Dayton. The CYD11G contained 1 gallon and 5 gallon paint cans. As we removed each inner container, one 5 gallon container of Thompson Deck Sealer that was leaking from the chime was identified. Veolia believes this material leaked into the inner liner where it pooled up at the bottom of the liner. While unpacking the CYD11G we also identified two Sawzall blades that were floating loosely in the bag.  Further investigation revealed several holes in the inner liner that we believe were caused by the saw blades. Our final determination was that the container of Thompson sealer was compromised and leaking in the bag and the saw blade compromised the bag during normal container handling operations. In our investigation we determined that a customer (HHW Visitor) must have brought us a box of paint cans that also contained the saw blades. The blades were likely on the bottom of a box concealed by various paint cans. Our employees took a quick look at the box and saw only paint-related material so they dumped the box into the CYD11G without realizing the blades were there.
column169: Veolia will use this incident as a safety moment for our team. We host several HHW events throughout the year and never know what hazards could be present in containers that are dropped off by the general public. We will also cover this during our hazard safety review meetings that we host before all HHW events. Lastly, we will use this as the talking point for our June EHS News Letter that is distributed within our branch.

column168: On May 24, 2021 at 13:00, a Virginia State Commerce Commission inspector reported to CSX that tank car TCIX 25052, load, Waste Flammable Liquids, Toxics, NOS, was found to have multiple loose manway covers bolts as well as a strong odor in the vicinity of the manway cover.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Clean Harbors, was notified.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the and found that 3 of the 8 manway cover swing bolts were less than tool tight resulting in the release of product odor/vapor.  Contractor personnel secured the loose closures which stopped the release of product vapor. Upon securement, the car was release for transportation.

column168: Yard employees reported a light smell of Chlorine in the receiving yard at West Colton Rail Yard.  Upon inspection of the area, AXLX 1205 was found releasing vapor from all four valves.  The valves were in the open position approximately 1/8 of a turn or less and the valve plugs were less than tool tight.  The valve handles were closed stopping the release and the valve plugs were secured to tool tight. UPRR Hazmat and San Bernadino County Hazmat took the offensive action in Level A chemical protective clothing.
column169: JCI Jones Chemical responded to the incident as subject matter experts and Chlorep responders.  JCI Jones Chemical has also conducted an internal investigation to determine root cause and evaluation to prevent future occurrences.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On May 12, 2021, at 12:45 hours personnel at Covington, VA reported observing tank car HOKX 112163, load, Sodium Hydroxide Solution, with hazardous residue adhering to the outside of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Occidental Chemical, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2021-0513-00113.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to inspect and correct the issue.  HEPACO reported finding less than a gallon of dried residue on the outside of the tank car.  The material appeared to have been released from the tank car’s pressure relief valve (PRV).  At the time of discovery there was no active leak from the tank car.  HEPACO did note that two of the manway cover bolts were less than tool tight however, this did not appear to be the source of the release.  The manway cover was opened to ensure proper volumetric outage of the product was not the cause of the release.  HEPACO verified adequate outage and secured the car for transportation.  The residue material was neutralized and rinse from the exterior of the car prior to the car being released back into transportation.

column168: Rail crews working in the Kenwood yard notice some residual product on car NATX 37160. Internal notifications made and external notifications requested from our dispatchers. Emergency response crews deployed and found a general service car that had released some methanol from the pressure relief device(PRD) on top of the car. Crews checked the pressure in the car and found aprox 65# on the car, interviews with crew indicated that while the car was being switched the PRD activated. Crews relieved the pressure on the car and removed 100-gallons from the car due to it being full. Estimated 2-gallons released and spill areas were cleaned up. CHEMTREC notified shipper and consignee.

SequenceEvent: Package was being loaded to the van by the driver when the leak was discovered. QA was immediately notified and the SDS found to properly administer first-aid and determine the severity of the situation. Any spill was limited to the driver's clothing and the lid of the pail and the driver was sent home to wash off any residual liquid and change clothing. (Driver is unharmed and returned to work the same day). Pail was contained in a haz bag and tote to be processed. DescribePack: Pail appears to be undamaged aside from the liquid that has stained and erased portions of the label. Pail is however vented and liquid is pooled around the cap, so it is likely either the cap or the vent itself. Cap was checked to determine if it was simply loose, it is not. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The SDS was found to determine the severity of the situation. Any spill was limited to the driver's clothing and the lid of the pail and the driver was sent home to wash off any residual liquid and change clothing. Pail was contained in a haz bag and tote to be processed and limit any further release.

column168: XPO Logistics XSX contacted ERTS regarding a hazardous cargo release, it was reported a 5 gallon pail of a UN3149 "Hydrogen Peroxide and Peroxyacetic Acid Mixture" was discovered damaged inside the trailer. ERTS determined a contractor would be necessary to respond for clean up. ERTS dispatched ESI to conduct cleanup operations. At 2256 EST, ESI personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 4 gallons of product released from a 5 gallon poly pail due to a puncture. The release impacted a 5' x 15' area of the trailer floor and a 5' x 20' area of the concrete lot below. The fire department was also on scene. Simple Green and granular absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged jug and all cleanup debris were placed into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The pallet was then re-stacked and re-wrapped. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Customer was unloading spent sulfuric acid from our trailer into their railcar when niaterial overflowed out the top onto the ground=- 50 gals. Driver was immediately instructed to leave the area to a safe location. Operator closed valve on our trailer and site personnel remediated the area and washed our trailer. No material entered any drains or waterways. There were no defects/malfunctions that caused the overflow. The railcar was never weighed prior to our trailer unloading into it and no other means for checking capacity was in place. Approx. 17,000 lbs. of material was still left in our trailer which could not be unloaded due to the railcar full beyond its capacity. It was rescheduled to retum at a later date.
column169: Going forward, Transflo/Veolia will open tankcar upon arrival at their terminal and take stick measurement of material in car to ensure there is enough room to accept the amount in our trailers to be offloaded. Standard practice to remain in place by Transflo is, they always take 10,000 lbs. off indicated weight to allow ample head space.

column168: On 05/06/2021 Shipment discovered to contain hidden DG during the physical inspection at the DHL LIC Service center located at 12-12 33rd Avenue Long Island City NY 11106 Transportation by road has been confirmed

Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package was shipped ground and was missing label information that would otherwise be contained in AWB stating that it is forbidden for transport aboard aircraft and vessel. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While traveling, a vehicle overturn resulted in the release of approximately 5,000 lbs of dry fertilizer into a roadside ditch. Local Police Department and Fire Department responded to assess the site. Tow Company was contracted to recover the vehicle, and CCD/PNE Corp was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, water was detected within the roadside ditch, a vacuum truck was utilized to recover approximately 1,500 gallons of liquid from within the ditch, and CCS/PNE proceeded to recover 2 truck loads of dry material from the impacted ditch. The area was secured with poly sheeting, pending analytical sampling results to determine further course of action. Upon receipt of sampling results, the bulk/majority of the cleanup had been performed; no product currently remains on-site and the immediate threat has been abated. After excavation, they identified a few locations through the analytical analysis that have very low concentration residual contamination exceeding background conditions. CCS/PNE Corp returned to the site to recover additional contamination and site was restored. There were no injuries or exposures reported.

column168: PVS Transportation driver was scheduled to deliver a shipment at Worthington Steel. Upon arrival to the customer site, the driver notified the operator there wouldn't be enough room to make the delivery when looking at the gauge. The operator, pumped product out of the tank in order to make enough room for the full delivery to fit. The operator told the driver to fill to 180 inches on the tank. When doing so the driver filled the entire tank and proceeded to blow his line clean. When doing so approximately 10 gallons of product overflowed into containment.
column169: In order to prevent any further releases from occurring, the Worthington Steel employee was trained on the importance of knowing how much product is in there tank. Also, we have asked Worthington Steel to provide the amount of product in gallons the tank can hold before a delivery can occur, that way the PVS Transportation driver will be able to double check the amount of product in the tank and determine how much product should be delivered into the customers tank.
